  <CalDefinition Description="Minimal trailing horizon length, see Appendix B. Note: The value range for this calibration is 0-500 meters, and the default value is 100 meters as defined in the GIS-628 Specification." Name="AHP_TrailingHorizonLength" References="GIS-628 Appendix B" Usage="MID,HIGH,GLOBALA,GLOBALB,VCU">
    <CalID>_RcE7EL5BEeO1CZP5M-nrYg</CalID>
    <Type>Integer</Type>
    <Version>4</Version>
    <CalDefChangeRecord>
      <Version>2</Version>
      <Date>2016-06-14</Date>
      <Description>Updated the untis , minimum, maximum, default and resolution values for this calibration. Trailing horizon length is important for being robust against inaccuracies of the positioning system (e.g., jumps in the vehicle offset), which may result in complete horizon rebuilt. Further, it determines how many data behind the vehicle an application will have to keep in its memory. Default setting is: 100m.</Description>
      <Author>Andreas Klein</Author>
    </CalDefChangeRecord>
    <CalDefChangeRecord>
      <Version>3</Version>
      <Date>2016-08-19</Date>
      <Description>Changed the units from km to meters, and updated the description to clarify that the units desired for this calibration should be in meters. With this update, also updated the resolution to 1 and updated the minimum, maximum, resolution, and default values to correspond to how this is defined in the GIS-628 Specification. Update the usage type from High to Mid and High.</Description>
      <Author>Andreas Klein</Author>
    </CalDefChangeRecord>
    <CalDefChangeRecord>
      <Version>4</Version>
      <Date>2017-06-02</Date>
      <Description>Updated usage field to support new &quot;Global A/B&quot; categorization in CalDef tool.</Description>
      <Author>Andreas Andrae</Author>
    </CalDefChangeRecord>
    <Integer>
      <Value>100</Value>
      <MinValue>0</MinValue>
      <MaxValue>500</MaxValue>
      <Units>m</Units>
      <Resolution>1.0</Resolution>
    </Integer>
  </CalDefinition>
